<TITLE> Upazila ordinance gets final approval </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 15 (bdnews24.com)The cabinet Sunday gave final approval to the Upazila Parishad Ordinance 2008 with a provision for a chairman and two vice-chairmen to be elected by direct vote. Of the two vice-chairmen, one must be a woman. "It has been made mandatory," the chief adviser's press secretary Syed Fahim Munaim told reporters after a meeting in the CA's office. The cabinet meeting chaired by chief adviser Fakhruddin Ahmed also approved Rangpur University Ordinance 2008 and decided to sign the amended charter of the Organisation of the Islamic Conference. Also, the cabinet meeting approved in principle a proposal for an amendment to Dhaka Electricity Distribution Act 1990. The amended law, when passed, will turn the DESA into Dhaka Power Distribution Company. "No DESA officials and employees would be terminated," Munaim said. UPAZILA ORDINANCE According to a provision in the Upazila Parishad ordinance, any case challenging the results of upazila elections must be filed in 30 days from the publication of a gazette on results. The case must be disposed of in 180 days from its filing and an appeal against the verdict must be submitted in 30 days and the verdict on the appeal must be delivered in 120 days, according to the ordinance. The law says political leaders could contest the polls but the elected people must give up their political posts before taking oath. Before the election, the candidates have to submit an affidavit to prove he is not unfit for the polls. The chairman and vice-chairmen will have to declare their wealth through affidavit during oath-taking. There is a provision in the ordinance for penalty for a delay in power transfer to an elected representative. The punishment may run up to three years in jail and Tk 20,000 in fine. The people will be ineligible to contest the polls if they are accused of defaulting on loans in the last one year before elections. If a person is punished for embezzlement of Upazila Parishad funds or is an absconding accused he will be ineligible to contest the upazila polls, according to the ordinance. Persons convicted as war criminals by any national or international court would be barred from contesting the upazila polls. bdnews24.com/e
